    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Furthermore, I think that you have mis-diagnosed the flake as one of network timeouts.\n\nIn the instances of the flake, the test completes in about 1 second, and the test log \"all replicas have pinged\" drops.\n\nSo, it's not that resource contention is causing pings to time out. The test completes successfully and then cancels the proxy server context (`s.ctx`) here.\n\nBut, the workspace proxy registers itself once at startup and then also kicks off a registration loop, which does a second registration and goes back through this code again. You can logs like this\n\n```\n     t.go:106: 2025-09-03 06:43:17.027 [debu]  re-registering workspace proxy with Coder primary  server_url=http://127.0.0.1:44777  req={\"access_url\":\"https://proxy1.test.coder.com\",\"wildcard_hostname\":\"\",\"derp_enabled\":true,\"derp_only\":false,\"replica_id\":\"8f914332-cde6-4707-8beb-91ed51236aee\",\"hostname\":\"depot-machine\",\"replica_error\":\"\",\"replica_relay_address\":\"http://127.0.0.1:44777\",\"version\":\"v0.0.0-devel\"}  timeout=10s  failed_attempts=0\n```\n\nThe race is that sometimes this second set of pings tied to re-registration happens with an expired `s.ctx` which immediately returns an error when we do the HTTP request. Thru the callback we eventually asserted that we got no error.",
    "commit_id": "f02c77a21bbbc8fdcc3738aac6d6e6b121b348ad",
    "created_at": "2025-10-15T08:05:50Z",
    "diff_hunk": "@@ -482,7 +483,13 @@ func (s *Server) handleRegister(res wsproxysdk.RegisterWorkspaceProxyResponse) e\n }\n \n func (s *Server) pingSiblingReplicas(replicas []codersdk.Replica) {\n-\tctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(s.ctx, 10*time.Second)\n+\t// Use a larger timeout for peer connectivity tests during testing.\n+\ttimeout := 10 * time.Second\n+\tif flag.Lookup(\"test.v\") != nil {",
